==English==
===Etymology===
First recorded use in the plays of Webster circa 1580; especially apropos the virtue of a Lady: 'her very soul and that other tenderness is there and theftable for any knave.'

===Noun===
'''Theftable'''

# An object or item that is theftable. that is that can be [[stolen]] or taken without [[consent]].

===Verb===
'''is theftable'''  (''present:'' '''[[theftable]]''')

# The car door was slightly ajar and had been left theftable.
# The man looked in through the window and scaned for items theftable
# She lay herself open to him her heart so theftable, for she loved him.


